= **<< [[[Anomalous Teens Against Trilobite Schemes]]] || Cafeteria Chat || [[[two-roads-diverge-tale | Two Roads Diverge (The 3009-C Remix)]]] >>**

----

â€œHey, can you pass the salt?â€

Junior Researcher Benedict Kim startled. It was December and the stale air of the Site-19 cafeteria reeked of rancid body odour and subpar budget meals. For the past hour in the cafeteriaâ€™s northwest corner, Junior Researcher Benedict Kim had sat uncomfortably at a table of near-strangers, united only by their Foundation jobs and their determination to ignore each other. 

But this stranger wasnâ€™t ignoring him. This stranger was trying to engage him in conversation. It was a terrifying upheaval of the established social order, especially considering that the salt was perfectly well within armâ€™s reach.

â€œUh,â€ said Benedict, with all the eloquence of a socially stunted sea slug. â€œYeah. Here.â€

He nudged the salt shaker marginally closer to his table mate. The other man picked up the shaker, spun it around handily, and shook an even layer of salt over his plate ofâ€¦ something. 

Despite himself, Benedict went in for a second look. On closer inspection, his lunch companion appeared to have ordered the Thursday Meat-Loaf Surprise, but the amorphous mass of porous, meaty brownness had been sliced into perfectly even cubes. This had the overall effect of transforming a fairly mediocre meal into a culinary masterpiece, straddling the border of modern art and affordably priced sustenance.

His lunch companion smiled charmingly and began consuming his meal in a series of quick, efficient bites. Benedictâ€™s phone buzzed in his pocket and he immediately fumbled to get it out, grateful for an excuse to avert his eyes and end the brief bit of conversation. 

Heâ€™d had a tough morning, courtesy of SCP-3009. For once, the [[[SCP-3009 | sapient snapchat account]]] hadnâ€™t actually done anything of note, but its continued existence and presence in Foundation custody seemed to generate endless amounts of paperwork. An encounter with a stranger was altogether too much stimulation for Benedict.

Then he actually looked at his phone, and any sense of relief for a distraction immediately faded.

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-incoming"]]3009[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-incoming"]]
so, iâ€™ve been thinking
you should let me talk to C again!!
[[/div]]

Benedict stared at his phone in a sort of dumbfounded frustration and struggled, fruitlessly, to string together a full sentence, preferably composed of vaguely tactful words. His brain, unfortunately, seemed to be malfunctioning. The words just werenâ€™t connecting.

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-incoming"]]3009[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-incoming"]]
great idea right?
[[/div]]

No. No, it wasnâ€™t. Or at least Benedict didnâ€™t think it was. What good could possible come of the two talking? There had been a good week when 3009-C, the fifteen year old humanoid that shared 3009â€™s identity, would burst into tears at the mere mention of its more obviously anomalous counterpart. 3009-C had been making good progress lately and had apparently developed a keen interest in psychology. It would be reckless and short-sighted to put all that at risk.

He expressed this sentiment by choking on his spaghetti. A clump of half chewed spaghetti flopped gracelessly out of his open mouth, and landed with a messy splatter onto his plate, flecking his plaid shirt with speckles of tomato sauce.

The stranger looked over at him in concern. â€œAre you okay?â€ 

â€œFine,â€ said Benedict hurriedly. â€œFine. Uh, yeah, fine.â€

â€œDo youâ€¦ need a napkin?â€

â€œNo. I mean. Yes. Actually. Thank you very much.â€

There was a brief, awkward kerfuffle as Benedict and his lunch companion both reached for the napkin dispenser simultaneously. The other man politely withdrew. With napkin in hand, Benedict dabbed gingerly at his shirt. The action just sort of spread the sauce around, causing it absorb into the fabric. 

The result, upon inspection, was significantly worse.

Giving up, Benedict picked up his phone again in an effort to ward off further social interaction.

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-incoming"]]3009[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-incoming"]]
the heck!!! 
donâ€™t leave me on read... ğŸ˜‘
you know I can see youâ€™ve opened the message right? 
anyone in, space case???? ğŸ˜’ğŸ˜’
[[/div]]

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-outgoing"]]Me[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-outgoing"]]
Iâ€™m not sure that talking to 3009-C at this stage is a good idea.
[[/div]]

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-incoming"]]3009[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-incoming"]]
why not? ğŸ˜¢
[[/div]]

[[span class="snapchat-sender snapchat-outgoing"]]Me[[/span]]
[[div class="snapchat snapchat-outgoing"]]
What are you hoping to talk to her about?
[[/div]]

His cellphone began to vibrate like an extraordinarily aggressive hornet. 3009 was trying to call him. Benedict glanced around. Lunch period was nearly over, and the cafeteria was fairly quiet. His table mate was watching him curiously.

â€œIâ€™m, uh, going to take this one,â€ Benedict said awkwardly, fumbling to lower the volume of his buzzing phone.

The stranger shrugged, turning away politely. â€œSure. Go for it. Donâ€™t mind me.â€

Reluctantly, he accepted the call. The face of fifteen-year-old Stacey Lee filled the screen as 3009 launched straight into its pitch.

â€œWell, to apologise, right? Like. I donâ€™t know. Offer anâ€¦ an olive branch! Of peace! And friendship!â€ As it talked, 3009 backed away from the screen and had begun gesticulating with such impressive speed that it was actually too much for Benedictâ€™s internet connection. Its arms had turned into a sort of off-white, hoodie-shaped blur. â€œAnd, like, give her some souvenirs in person. How else am I going to fix things?â€ 

Benedict shrank back into his seat, wishing heâ€™d gone outside to the bathrooms to take the call. It seemed by far too awkward to try leaving now. â€œThatâ€™s really wonderful, 3009, but sheâ€™s making some good progress, you know, andâ€”â€œ He paused, confused. â€œWhat souvenirs?â€

â€œYou know,â€ said 3009 impatiently. â€œLike the bear video! And that piece of the wall!â€

A piece of wallâ€¦ Benedict gaped at 3009, amazed. So //that// was why Researcher Xiulan had mailed him a piece of rubble after the whole disaster at Site-201. It had been a souvenir. Heâ€™d thought it had been some kind of advanced hazing tactic. Or perhaps a threat of some kind.

â€œIâ€™d have to get it approved,â€ said Benedict distractedly.  â€œI donâ€™tâ€¦ really have that power. Even if I thought it was a good idea. Which I donâ€™t, for the record.â€

3009 huffed, crossing its arms. â€œWhat? Itâ€™s totally a good idea!â€ 

Benedict glanced around awkwardly, and noticed that his lunch companion was watching him. There was a curious expression on his face.

â€œUh,â€ said Benedict awkwardly.

â€œOh, sorry.â€ The other man chuckled awkwardly. â€œIs thatâ€¦ your younger sister?â€ The unspoken question was obvious: //Is that a civilian?//

3009 tensed onscreen. It had fallen awkwardly silent.

â€œUm. No,â€ Benedict paused, and looked his table mate up and down for the first time. He didnâ€™t //look// much like a researcher, but he was obviously affiliated with the Foundation in some way, and 3009 wasnâ€™t particularly classified information. â€œThis is SCP-3009. Itâ€™s an entity tied to a snapchat account. Iâ€™m responsible for fulfilling its social needs.â€

â€œHow fascinating. I think Iâ€™ve heard a little about that case. Very interesting. So you must be on the 3009 research team?â€

â€œYes,â€ said Benedict. â€œJunior Researcher Benedict Kim. Nice to meet you.â€

The man nodded, with an apologetic smile. â€œSorry, I didnâ€™t mean to interrupt your conversation. Iâ€™m [[[Ethics | Agent Johnson.]]] Itâ€™s a pleasure.â€

That caught 3009â€™s attention. â€œAgent,â€ it repeated, suddenly interested. â€œYou mean thereâ€™s people here who arenâ€™t, like, scientists?â€

Johnson caught Benedictâ€™s eye, questioningly. When Benedict nodded, Johnson smiled reassuringly. â€œYes,â€ he said. â€œA field agent. It means that I help the Foundation with work that they have outside.â€

3009 seemed extremely impressed by this. On screen, Stacey Lee sucked in a slow breath and nodded slowly. â€œWow, like James Bond! Awesome. I thought you had to be, likeâ€¦ super sciencey to work with the Foundation.â€

â€œAh, no,â€ said Johnson. â€œThere are lots of different things that the Foundation needs people to do. I just help out where Iâ€™m needed, you know?â€

â€œThatâ€™s so cool,â€ 3009 said, fascinated. â€œDo you do a lot of cool things? It sounds like a fun job. Like something out of a comic book.â€

Something flickered oddly in Agent Johnsonâ€™s eyes, but the moment passed so quickly that Benedict wondered if it had been his imagination, or perhaps a trick with the fluorescent lighting.

â€œWell, I do a lot of helpful things,â€ said Johnson tactfully. His smile suddenly seemed extremely bland. 

//Like something out of a comic bookâ€¦// Benedict couldnâ€™t imagine, to be honest, that Agent Johnsonâ€™s job was all sunshine and rainbows. 

The Foundation did need a lot of work to get done, and not all of it was pleasant. Like removing fifteen-year-old girls from their homes and putting them under permanent protective custody. And even that was thoroughly insignificant, when compared to the other things that the Foundation did. The 3009 situation was barely a blip on the Foundation radar.

Benedict startled. The conversation had moved on without him. Agent Johnson and 3009 were chatting amiably. They didnâ€™t look like a Foundation agent and a skip making conversation. Agent Johnson seemed almost like a particularly friendly teacher, chatting to a prized student.

â€œâ€¦which is wonderful, and I couldnâ€™t help but notice that the two of you have a very close relationship,â€ Agent Johnson was saying. â€œDo you admire what Researcher Kim does?â€

â€œUh, I guess,â€ said 3009. â€œI mean, Bennyâ€™s a cool guy, deep down! I, um, donâ€™t really know much about what he does, but it seems super cool. Iâ€™m not very good at science, though.â€

â€œBut youâ€™d like to help the Foundation in other ways, if you could?â€ said Johnson, curiously.

â€œIâ€¦â€ 3009 hesitated, momentarily. â€œI guess so. I mean, Iâ€™d like to be useful, you know?â€

Agent Johnson smiled. Heâ€™d finished his food at some point, and had started clearing his section of the table. â€œThatâ€™s excellent. A wonderful goal. Iâ€™m sure that thereâ€™s some way you can be more useful.â€

â€œYou think so?â€ said 3009 hopefully.

â€œIâ€™m positive,â€ said Johnson. He rose from his seat and picked up his tray. â€œWell, I have some errands to run, but it was a pleasure meeting you both.â€

Benedict tried imagined what it might like, for 3009 to be â€œmore usefulâ€ to the Foundation. The thought made him strangely uncomfortable, but it was difficult to put into words why he felt that way. 

â€œAnd you!â€ 3009 chirped. â€œCome talk to me again some time! Tell me about all your awesome adventures!â€

â€œWell, itâ€™s classified stuff,â€ said Johnson with a smile, turning to leave. â€œBut Iâ€™ll do my best. Have a great day.â€

â€œSame to you,â€ said Benedict, a few seconds too late, but heâ€™d timed it wrong and Johnson was already out of earshot.

----
